<section id="about" class="fade-in">
  <span class="sec-lbl" id="lAbout">About Arunachal Pradesh</span>
  <h2 class="sec-title" id="aboutTitle">Where <em>India Sees the First Light</em></h2>
  <p class="sec-body" id="aboutBody">Arunachal Pradesh — literally "Land of the Dawn-Lit Mountains" (Aruna = dawn, Achal = mountains) — is the easternmost state of India and the first place on the subcontinent to receive the rising sun each morning. This vast, breathtaking frontier covers 83,743 sq km — larger than Austria — and shares borders with China, Bhutan and Myanmar. It is the largest state in Northeast India and one of India's most ecologically and culturally extraordinary places. The Eastern Himalayas here rise from sub-tropical rainforests at 100 meters to alpine meadows at 7,000 meters in a single valley — a biodiversity gradient found nowhere else on earth. Arunachal Pradesh is home to more species of orchid (600+ species) than any other region in the world, more species of rhododendron than anywhere outside the Himalayas, and forests of sal, teak, bamboo and pine that remain largely intact because the state's terrain has never allowed industrialized logging. The Brahmaputra river — called the Siang in Arunachal — enters India here from Tibet through one of the world's deepest gorges, carving the Great Bend of the Himalayas. Arunachal Pradesh is home to over 26 major tribes and more than 100 sub-tribes, each with their own language, religion, dress, dance and architecture. The Adi, Nyishi, Galo, Apatani, Monpa, Wancho, Nocte, Tangsa and dozens of other communities have lived in these mountains and valleys for thousands of years with a relationship to the land and forest that is irreplaceable and deeply sophisticated. The Tawang Monastery — one of the largest Buddhist monasteries in Asia outside Tibet — stands at 10,000 feet, founded in the 17th century, watching over the valley where the 6th Dalai Lama was born. The Ziro Valley — a UNESCO World Heritage nominee — is a breathtaking landscape of pine-forested hills and terraced paddy fields where the Apatani tribe's agriculture is a masterpiece of sustainable farming. The Namdapha National Park in the east is one of the world's most biodiverse protected areas — the only park in the world with four big cat species (tiger, leopard, snow leopard and clouded leopard). This is Arunachal: ancient, misty, alive and the first dawn in India.</p>
</section>
