const placesData=[
{emoji:"🏔️",name:"Tawang Monastery",location:"Tawang District",desc:"The second-largest Buddhist monastery in Asia after the Potala Palace in Lhasa — founded in the 17th century at 10,000 feet in the Tawang Valley, birthplace of the 6th Dalai Lama. The 400-year-old monastery houses 500 monks, an extraordinary library of ancient scriptures and sacred Buddhist relics. The view of the monastery rising from mountain mist above the Tawang river valley, surrounded by Himalayan peaks, is one of India's most spectacular sights.",fee:["Rs.50 camera fee"]},
{emoji:"🌾",name:"Ziro Valley",location:"Lower Subansiri District",desc:"A UNESCO World Heritage Site nominee — a breathtaking valley of pine-forested hills and terraced paddy fields inhabited by the Apatani tribe. The Apatani practice one of India's most sophisticated and sustainable agricultural systems — growing rice and fish simultaneously in the same paddy fields at 5,500 feet, creating a living tradition 2,000 years old. The winter Ziro Music Festival brings indie music to this extraordinary Himalayan landscape.",fee:["ILP required"]},
{emoji:"🐅",name:"Namdapha National Park",location:"Changlang District",desc:"The most biodiverse national park in India — 1,985 sq km ranging from 200 to 4,500 meters, the only park in the world sheltering four big cat species: Bengal tiger, leopard, snow leopard and clouded leopard. Also home to red pandas, gibbons, sun bears, Asian elephants and over 1,000 plant species. The Namdapha flying squirrel — found nowhere else — was only discovered in 1981. The park remains almost entirely unexplored.",fee:["Paid"]},
{emoji:"🦅",name:"Eaglenest Wildlife Sanctuary",location:"West Kameng District",desc:"The finest birdwatching site in the Indian subcontinent — a gradient forest from 100 to 3,000 meters sheltering over 450 bird species including 8 globally threatened species. The Bugun liocichla — a new bird species discovered here in 2006 — was found by amateur birdwatcher Ramana Athreya and is one of the rarest birds on earth. Eaglenest consistently tops national birding surveys as the single best birdwatching site in India.",fee:["Paid + ILP required"]},
{emoji:"🌸",name:"Mechuka Valley",location:"West Siang District",desc:"An extraordinarily remote valley at 6,000 feet near the China border — surrounded by snow-capped peaks, with the Yargyap river flowing through meadows of wildflowers. The medieval Samten Yungdrung Monastery sits above the valley. Called the 'Hidden Shangri-La', Mechuka was only accessible by road in 2008. The Adi and Memba communities here maintain living traditions of remarkable depth. April brings rhododendron blooms across every hillside.",fee:["ILP + permits required"]},
{emoji:"🏔️",name:"Sela Pass",location:"Tawang District",desc:"A high mountain pass at 13,700 feet on the road to Tawang — one of the highest passes in the world that remains open year-round. The Sela Lake at the pass turns a vivid deep blue under the Himalayan sky. In winter, the pass is thick with snow; in October, the surrounding mountains are ablaze with autumn color. The drive up through cloud forest to reach the pass, then down into the Tawang valley, is one of India's great mountain road journeys.",fee:["Free — ILP required for beyond"]},
{emoji:"🙏",name:"Parasuram Kund",location:"Lohit District",desc:"One of Hinduism's most sacred pilgrimage sites in Northeast India — a natural kund (pool) in the Lohit river gorge where sage Parasuram is said to have washed away the sin of killing his mother. On Makar Sankranti (January), thousands of pilgrims descend from across India to bathe. The site's setting — the Lohit river thundering through a forested gorge with the Eastern Himalayas above — is of extraordinary natural beauty.",fee:["Free — ILP required"]},
{emoji:"🌸",name:"Sangti Valley — Black-Necked Cranes",location:"West Kameng District",desc:"A serene valley at 6,500 feet that hosts the rare black-necked crane (Grus nigricollis) every winter — one of only two sites in India where these sacred birds overwinter. The cranes are revered by the Monpa tribe as divine messengers. The valley of apple orchards, prayer flags and mountain backdrop creates a landscape that feels closer to Tibet than India. The arrival of the cranes in November is an event of profound local significance.",fee:["ILP required"]},
{emoji:"🏞️",name:"Anini — Dibang Valley",location:"Dibang Valley District",desc:"The most remote district headquarters in India — Anini in the Dibang Valley can only be reached by a dramatic mountain road or helicopter. The Idu Mishmi tribal community here maintains one of India's most isolated and sophisticated cultures — their oral literature, shamanic traditions and knowledge of forest medicine are extraordinary. The surrounding Dibang Valley wilderness is one of the last truly wild landscapes in India.",fee:["ILP + restricted area permit"]},
{emoji:"⛩️",name:"Golden Pagoda, Namsai",location:"Namsai District",desc:"The largest Buddhist pagoda in Northeast India — the Kongmu Kham temple complex at Namsai was built by the Theravada Buddhist Tai Khamti community in 2010. The gilded structure rising from a flat landscape near the Myanmar border is a stunning visual surprise. The Tai Khamti community's Buddhist traditions, distinct from the Tibetan Buddhism of Tawang, represent the southeastern Buddhist influence that entered Arunachal from Burma.",fee:["Free"]}
