{emoji:"🪘",name:"Tribal Mask Carving & Wood Craft",location:"Wancho (Longding), Nocte (Tirap)",desc:"The Wancho and Nocte tribes of eastern Arunachal create some of India's most powerful carved wooden objects — ancestor posts (morang), log drums, warrior shields and ceremonial masks painted with geometric patterns. The morang (bachelor dormitory) is decorated with carvings that record the village's history. Wancho mask-making is practiced by community specialists and the masks are used in ceremonies connecting the living and the dead."},
{emoji:"🎵",name:"Tribal Music — Flutes, Drums and Song",location:"Statewide",desc:"Arunachal's tribal music cultures are among India's most diverse. The Adi's ponung dance with its characteristic wailing melodic chorus; the Monpa's dungchen (long Buddhist horns) and cymbals in monastery ceremonies; the Nyishi's bamboo flute traditions; the Wancho's log drum communication — each is a distinct musical universe. The instruments are almost entirely made from forest materials: bamboo, hide, bone and wood."},
{emoji:"🏺",name:"Apatani Crafts & Agriculture Heritage",location:"Ziro Valley, Lower Subansiri",desc:"The Apatani tribe is famous not only for its remarkable terraced paddy-fish farming system but for its distinctive crafts: bamboo baskets of extraordinary precision (used for storing everything from grain to sacred objects), cane work, traditional costumes with blue tattoos (now discontinued) and the distinctive noshi nose plugs worn by older women. The Apatani's agricultural knowledge — documented by UNESCO — is a living library of sustainable mountain farming."},
