{emoji:"🥁",name:"Ponung — Adi Harvest Dance",location:"East and West Siang — Post Harvest",desc:"The Adi tribe's most important festival — Ponung is a community dance performed by women in a circle, led by a miri (priest) who chants the tribe's oral history and mythology. The dance can last all night and involves intricate synchronized arm and body movements. It is simultaneously an agricultural thanksgiving, a history lesson and a community binding ritual. Each verse of the chant is unique to each miri — the tradition is oral and unrepeatable."},
{emoji:"🎉",name:"Nyokum Festival — Nyishi",location:"Nyishi Areas — February",desc:"The most important festival of the Nyishi tribe — a thanksgiving to the earth deity Nyokum for the blessings of harvest, health and prosperity. Performed at a ritually constructed altar (yullo) where the priest (nyibu) invokes the spirits with chants and offerings. The festival includes community feasting, traditional dancing and the slaughter of mithun (a semi-wild bovine sacred to Arunachali tribes). The nyibu's chanted prayers are complex oral literature."},
{emoji:"🌿",name:"Solung — Adi Agricultural Festival",location:"East Siang — September",desc:"The Adi tribe's most important agricultural festival — a five-day celebration at the end of the planting season with elaborate rituals, community feasting, mithun sacrifice and the mopun (collective) dances. The festival invokes Doiing and Uie — the ancestral spirits — for a bountiful harvest. Young men demonstrate their prowess through mock battles (mithun battles symbolically enacted) and the community re-affirms its bonds through collective labor and eating."},
