const cuisinesData=[
{emoji:"🎋",name:"Bamboo Shoot Preparations",location:"Statewide — All Tribal Kitchens",desc:"Bamboo shoot is the defining ingredient of Arunachali cuisine — fresh shoots eaten as vegetable, fermented shoots used as a souring agent (replacing tamarind in lowland Indian cooking), dried shoots stored for year-round use. Every tribe prepares bamboo shoot differently: the Adi ferments it in bamboo tubes for months to create a pungent, deeply flavored condiment; the Monpa uses it in soups with yak meat; the Apatani adds it to fish preparations."},
{emoji:"🍖",name:"Smoked Meat — Pork & Mithun",location:"Statewide",desc:"Smoking over a wood fire is the primary preservation technique across Arunachal's tribal kitchens — pork, wild boar, chicken, dried fish and the prized mithun (the semi-wild Bos frontalis, sacred to Arunachali tribes) are all smoked to extraordinary depth of flavor. The smoke imparts a complex earthiness impossible to replicate. Smoked pork with bamboo shoot and dried chilies is the quintessential Adi and Nyishi dish — robust, ancient and deeply satisfying."},
{emoji:"🫗",name:"Apong — Rice Beer",location:"Statewide",desc:"Apong (Adi), chi (Monpa) and poka (Nyishi) — rice beer brewed in bamboo tubes or clay pots with yeast derived from forest plants — is central to every tribal ceremony, festival and act of hospitality in Arunachal Pradesh. Offering apong to a guest is the highest expression of welcome. The flavor varies from sweet and mild (freshly brewed) to sour and complex (fermented for weeks). Refusing apong is considered deeply impolite."},
{emoji:"🍜",name:"Thukpa & Tibetan-Influenced Dishes",location:"Tawang — Monpa Region",desc:"The Monpa cuisine of Tawang is strongly Tibetan-influenced — thukpa (noodle soup with meat and vegetables), tsampa (roasted barley flour eaten with yak butter tea), tingmo (steamed bread), momos (dumplings filled with yak meat or vegetables) and the butter tea (po cha) itself — a blend of strong black tea, yak butter and salt that takes considerable getting used to but is a lifeline at 10,000 feet in bitter cold."},
{emoji:"🌿",name:"Pika Pila — Fermented Fish",location:"Lower Subansiri, Ziro Valley",desc:"The Apatani tribe's most distinctive ingredient — fish fermented with mustard leaves and salt, then stored in bamboo containers for months. The resulting pika pila has an intensely sour, fermented flavor that transforms every dish it touches. Combined with bamboo shoot and dried chilies, it creates a curry of extraordinary complexity. The Apatani's fish-rice farming system means fresh fish is always available — fermented fish is the way to preserve the surplus through seasons."},
{emoji:"🥣",name:"Marua — Millet Preparations",location:"Higher Elevation Districts",desc:"Finger millet (marua) is a staple grain at higher elevations — ground into flour and made into thick porridge, flatbread or fermented into the millet beer chi drunk in Monpa and Sherdukpen areas. Marua contains more calcium and iron than rice and is perfectly adapted to the cold growing conditions of high-altitude Arunachal. The grain is stored in elevated wooden granaries that are architectural features in themselves."},
{emoji:"🍲",name:"Kholam — Rice Cooked in Bamboo",location:"Adi Areas, East Siang",desc:"Rice cooked inside a bamboo tube over an open fire — the bamboo imparts a subtle woody fragrance to the rice and the cooking method is ingeniously simple. Kholam is festival food for the Adi tribe — prepared for community gatherings and ceremonies. The sealed bamboo tube steams the rice perfectly; when split open at the table, the aroma of bamboo-scented rice is extraordinary. A technique 2,000 years old, now recognized by food anthropologists worldwide."},
{emoji:"🌶️",name:"Zan — Millet Mash",location:"Arunachal Tribal Communities",desc:"Zan is the fundamental everyday food of many Arunachali tribes — a thick stiff mash of millet or maize flour cooked with water until dense, eaten with pickled bamboo shoot, smoked meat or dried fish. Filling, nutritious and requiring no elaborate preparation, zan has sustained mountain farmers and hunters for generations. Each tribe has its own version — some incorporate leafy forest greens directly into the mash."}
